In 656 , after editing by Li Chunfeng , the treatise Zhui shu ( Method of Interpolation ) became a text for the Imperial examinations and it became one of The Ten Classics when reprinted in 1084 . However, the Zhui shu was too advanced for the students at the Imperial Academy and it was dropped from the syllabus for that reason. This almost certainly explains why the text has not survived, being lost in the early twelfth century.
In the latter part of his life Zu Chongzhi collaborated with his son, Zu Geng ( or Zu Xuan ) , who was also an outstanding mathematician.
